us started, can I have you both introduce yourselves and share a little bit about each

00:03:10.679 --> 00:03:17.360
of your roles? Yeah. So my name is Matthew Iorio. I'm the senior manager of clinical

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:24.960
affairs and data analytics at Neuros Medical. I joined the company in 2004 as an intern

00:03:24.960 --> 00:03:29.919
and now kind of help to oversee all patient reported outcome data collection as well as

00:03:29.919 --> 00:03:35.320
clinical data science activities within the company. It'll be great to talk about with

00:03:35.320 --> 00:03:39.240
everybody today is kind of the evolution of this department as it's grown in parallel

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:45.679
with our recently completed Quest IDE trial and the different kinds of data analytics

00:03:45.679 --> 00:03:50.199
and data science type activities we have going on there in a small neuromodulation startup.

00:03:50.199 --> 00:03:56.600
So great to be here with everybody. Thank you. And Ramil, you want to introduce

00:03:56.600 --> 00:04:02.360
yourself, too? Yeah. So my name is Ramil. I do data analysis

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:07.960
here at Neuros, help build tools and data pipelines here to really support our clinical

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:12.919
operations team. Yeah. And it's cool to be doing this.

00:04:12.919 --> 00:04:20.160
Thank you both for joining us. And so I guess to kind of kick things off here, I know you

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:26.160
just mentioned about building this team, Matt. Can you tell me a little bit about the founding

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:30.399
of the company's clinical data department from the ground up?

00:04:30.399 --> 00:04:39.480
Yeah. So I joined in 2014 as an intern right when our pivotal phase three trial, the Quest

00:04:39.480 --> 00:04:45.720
study started. And as we were going through that, kind of the kind of the foundation there

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:51.359
was the way we were collecting data at the time essentially was we had patients reporting

00:04:51.359 --> 00:04:55.239
their pain levels and medication use on what we had, what we had designed as an e-diary,

00:04:55.320 --> 00:05:01.480
right? So they had a cell phone and an app on that phone that would collect data. And

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:05.720
typically the two ways of data collection were from that as well as paper case report

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:10.600
forms once we started the trial. So not to date ourselves there, but we used paper case

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:15.720
report forms at the sites to gather information on the patients when they would come in for

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:19.559
their visits and programming sessions for the Alteus device.

00:05:20.359 --> 00:05:23.799
One other thing to kind of, I think, give people some background if they're not familiar

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:29.880
with neuros, just to kind of kind of lay that groundwork. We're a clinical stage neuromodulation

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:36.040
company. We're developing the Alteus system to help patients with chronic lower limb post

00:05:36.040 --> 00:05:42.359
amputation pain. So these patients would be enrolled and implanted in our trial that would

00:05:42.359 --> 00:05:48.359
not receive adequate pain relief for any other kind of standards of care, be it opiates or

00:05:48.359 --> 00:05:54.440
gabapentanoids or any other kinds of surgeries. And in the US alone, we have around 185,000

00:05:54.440 --> 00:06:00.040
amputations every year, mainly a lot of those due to cardiovascular disease and diabetes,

00:06:00.040 --> 00:06:05.720
and as well as trauma for various kinds of accidents and things like that. So there's

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:13.799
a high demand and high levels of these patients have chronic pain post amputation. So the

00:06:13.799 --> 00:06:18.359
Alteus system is our technology to kind of ideally relieve their pain and restore their

00:06:18.359 --> 00:06:23.799
lives, as we say at Neuros. And when patients would use the device, we would have them report

00:06:23.799 --> 00:06:29.000
this information in their e-diaries. So they would report multiple times a day, every single day.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:34.279
And then they would also report pain levels at the end of the day, as well as their medication use.

00:06:34.839 --> 00:06:40.359
And so when we started this trial in 2014, we collected a lot of the data on the e-diary with

00:06:40.359 --> 00:06:45.559
one of our vendors at the time, as well as paper case report forms at the sites for those particular

00:06:45.559 --> 00:06:53.399
visits. As we evolved over time and as more and more patients enrolled, we started to see the

00:06:53.399 --> 00:06:59.559
need also internally to have more of an operational focus around the data as well. What I mean by that

00:06:59.559 --> 00:07:05.480
is, as probably you can imagine, as patients get implanted, we have more and more patients going

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:10.519
on. We have more and more study visits happening. And at the time, probably around 2020, so right

00:07:10.519 --> 00:07:15.559
around like the height of the pandemic, the Quest study was really taken off. We had a lot of

00:07:15.559 --> 00:07:21.959
implanted subjects and we had a lot of need to coordinate data information and coordinate

00:07:21.959 --> 00:07:26.760
resources at the sites because we needed field staff to be supporting the sites. And we also

00:07:26.760 --> 00:07:31.880
needed to know which patients were going to potentially be implanted and kind of the progress

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:37.480
of all of them. And so at that point, the clinical team, myself and other members of the team, were

00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:42.519
getting a lot of outside requests from other departments because we needed to coordinate

00:07:42.519 --> 00:07:49.000
to make sure that we could support those visits. So we were getting asked a lot of different

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:54.200
requests. And at that time, we did not have the foundation to really process these requests from

00:07:54.200 --> 00:08:00.519
an operational point of view, traditionally using certain tools like Excel, for instance, right? So

00:08:01.399 --> 00:08:08.119
my background is in biomedical engineering, so I have programming experience. So in 2020, I decided,

00:08:08.119 --> 00:08:13.399
well, I got to start programming again so that we can possibly, you know, kind of keep up with

00:08:13.399 --> 00:08:18.440
these requests so we can make sure that our patients are well supported and so are our sites

00:08:18.440 --> 00:08:24.760
and that we have all the adequate staff there. So I randomly picked up Python in 2020.

00:08:25.399 --> 00:08:31.320
And then as we kind of went along and we got closer to finishing quests and we knew the other

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:36.840
side of the data trial would be, how do we start to analyze this data along with our vendors, right,

00:08:36.840 --> 00:08:42.200
to prepare for submission for FDA? And so we kind of need some more horsepower. We're going to need

00:08:42.200 --> 00:08:47.159
more people that can kind of help kind of crunch these numbers, support the trial as it's coming to

00:08:47.159 --> 00:08:54.359
a close, as well as process this information. So in 2022, we hired two clinical data employees,

00:08:54.919 --> 00:09:01.320
both with programming experience in R. Ramil was one of them. Ramil was our first focused,

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:07.640
fully focused data hire that we had at Nero's. Another one of our employees kind of does a

00:09:07.640 --> 00:09:12.679
hybrid role where he does operations, clinical operations, as well as some programming experience.

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:18.280
And the one thing that I realized at that point was that these guys can really program in R.

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:24.760
And I said, well, I'm going to move over and start to do that too. So 2022 onward,

00:09:24.760 --> 00:09:28.760
our role has really shifted to not only supporting the close of the quest study,

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:35.479
but also supporting the validation efforts of our tables and figures and listings for the FDA

00:09:35.479 --> 00:09:43.400
submission, as well as post hoc analyses as we move ahead. So currently, today at Nero's,

00:09:43.400 --> 00:09:47.400
we're a pretty small company in general, but today, currently we have two full-time

00:09:48.119 --> 00:09:53.000
clinical data employees with some consultants and vendors as well. We have people, certain people,

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:57.559
focus on the safety side and mainly us on the effectiveness, as well as, you know,

00:09:57.559 --> 00:10:02.599
obviously kind of covering all of that data. And we're also responsible now for helping to

00:10:02.599 --> 00:10:07.320
generate data for publications and presentations, investor meetings, and things like that. So we

00:10:07.320 --> 00:10:13.080
kind of do it all now. And the goal is to be as good of a partner as we can cross-functionally

00:10:13.080 --> 00:10:17.799
and always have the mission in mind that our patients come first as we develop these tools

00:10:17.799 --> 00:10:20.520
and pipelines and efficiencies so we can move the company forward.

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:30.760
Thank you for that background. And Ramil, I'm curious to hear from you too about your experience

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:34.679
joining a company as one of the first data science hires as well.

00:10:35.159 --> 00:10:44.039
Yeah, so it's funny because I was doing my graduate schooling for applied stats and looking

00:10:44.039 --> 00:10:50.520
for an internship. Fortunately, Mal was able to pick me up full-time and I was able to do

00:10:50.520 --> 00:11:00.919
both concurrently. And I will say, you know, prior to being here, it's a lot of it, you know,

00:11:01.159 --> 00:11:09.880
a lot of it, you know, I thought was ML and AI. And really, it's the complete opposite. I think,

00:11:09.880 --> 00:11:16.679
especially as a startup company, there's a lot of just data cleaning and some things that,

00:11:18.840 --> 00:11:26.200
you know, you don't need ML and AI for. And apart from that, really learning about the

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:33.320
rigor in clinical trials and building a data team from the ground up. So being a part of that has

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:40.200
been, for myself, a huge learning. And yeah, continue to learn every day.

00:11:43.239 --> 00:11:49.640
I think that's so important to stress that it's not all about AI and ML. And sometimes people

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:54.359
can think that looking into even some of these like big companies who are presenting here that

00:11:55.159 --> 00:11:59.640
are not doing some of those like data cleaning activities too.

00:12:01.880 --> 00:12:07.080
I have a few questions, but I want to make sure I'm jumping into questions that you all want to

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:13.159
ask here too. I know in the beginning, I get to ask a lot of mine, but I wanted to continue on

00:12:13.159 --> 00:12:21.719
this, like starting as a first data scientist track and ask you, Matt, what were you looking

00:12:21.719 --> 00:12:26.200
for when you're hiring and what makes a good data science hire for some of us that are

00:12:26.919 --> 00:12:33.880
starting to hire too? Yeah, I think that's a really great question. So I kind of alluded to

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:43.479
it first, is that I kind of knew the need that we had. So for me, I have a pretty long history

00:12:43.479 --> 00:12:48.599
of programming, but we needed more people that could handle that, right? To continue to increase

00:12:48.599 --> 00:12:52.520
the quality and maintain the quality that we had and make sure that we were asserting our

00:12:52.520 --> 00:12:57.159
clinical sites, make sure that we were helping our cross-functional partners within the company,

00:12:58.039 --> 00:13:02.760
make sure that we could execute the trial at an extremely high level, right? And always be there

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:07.960
for our patients. The other thing that was important with this was that I really wanted

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:16.520
somebody personally that could push me to be better. And Ramil was that. Ramil also had a great

00:13:16.919 --> 00:13:21.880
passion for using data science and analytics and his background in statistics to

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:27.479
help human health. So one of the things that intrigued me really about Ramil and kind of

00:13:27.479 --> 00:13:33.080
his interview process was on his GitHub page, you know, he has family members that have various

00:13:33.080 --> 00:13:38.599
health conditions and he was trying to solve data issues with that, you know, in his initiative as

00:13:38.599 --> 00:13:45.400
well. And we, you know, at Neuros, top to bottom, side to side, the mission is clear about relieving

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:50.760
pain and restoring the lives of these patients and looking for someone as well who has that

00:13:50.760 --> 00:13:58.280
passion to do that is really critical. I think, you know, as well that, you know, as a kind of

00:13:58.280 --> 00:14:03.799
seeing this is, I think if you have a good foundation in programming or some of these tools,

00:14:04.440 --> 00:14:08.440
you may not necessarily need to know the exact tool to be successful at a company,

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:12.919
because it's just like speaking another language. So the ability to learn and want to learn that

00:14:12.919 --> 00:14:19.080
attention to detail and being patient focused for us was really critical for that. Obviously,

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:25.000
you have to have a foundation in that as well, as well as programming and a strong foundation. But,

00:14:25.559 --> 00:14:30.200
you know, to be able to see, can you pick up the details and the data that are super critical? Can

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:36.359
you take the time and you have strong fundamentals? But more importantly, are you motivated? Are you

00:14:36.359 --> 00:14:39.719
passionate about what you do? And are you passionate about helping the patients in our,

00:14:39.719 --> 00:14:48.679
for our company? It's really critical. Absolutely. So I know you mentioned FDA submissions in the

00:14:48.679 --> 00:14:55.320
beginning, and we have talked a lot about FDA submissions in the Hangout. And I know there's

00:14:55.320 --> 00:15:01.479
so many different kinds as well. Can you just talk a little bit more about that process?

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:11.159
Yeah, so I guess at a high level, Neuros, the Alteus device is a class three medical device. So

00:15:12.440 --> 00:15:17.000
highest level classification in terms of because of the way it's implanted in the body. And as you

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:21.239
could, if anybody, to kind of give everybody a picture, the Alteus system is essentially like a

00:15:21.239 --> 00:15:26.840
generator that's implanted in the body, similar to a pacemaker, cardiac pacemaker. And then there's

00:15:26.840 --> 00:15:32.840
an electrode that goes down and attaches to the nerve that was amputated in the lower limb.

00:15:33.559 --> 00:15:39.799
And the device delivers high frequency electron electrical stimulation to the nerve.

00:15:41.559 --> 00:15:47.640
And the idea is that that signal will dampen the pain signals coming from the nerve to the central

00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:53.239
nervous system. So the patient would feel less pain. So for this kind of device, it's classified

00:15:53.239 --> 00:15:58.280
as a class three device. It's never been on the market before. So because of that, the invasiveness

00:15:58.280 --> 00:16:04.919
in terms of implanting the data, the implanted device, I mean, we had to go through the PMA

00:16:04.919 --> 00:16:13.320
process for FDA submission. So that consists of obviously early on with the inventors,

00:16:13.960 --> 00:16:19.799
Drs. Kevin Kilgore and Neelay Bhadra, developing the device in the lab, doing animal testing on it.

00:16:20.359 --> 00:16:25.799
Then you move to like a small patient pilot, like a first in human study. So like a handful of

00:16:25.799 --> 00:16:33.640
patients. We use that data to then catapult us to about a 10 patient pilot study. The data got

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:37.640
really good results. The device got really good results. That information allowed the FDA to say,

00:16:37.640 --> 00:16:44.200
yeah, go ahead with Quest, right? So then we implanted 180 patients from that study.

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:50.119
And now the process after the study closed was we have to pull all of the data together

00:16:51.400 --> 00:17:00.119
per an agreed upon statistical analysis plan with the FDA. So sponsor and FDA go back and forth on

00:17:00.119 --> 00:17:05.560
what to include, what not to include, and why. And then you have to kind of stick to that. So

00:17:05.560 --> 00:17:12.520
to Ramil's point, a lot of that can be more of your standard statistical analysis algorithms,

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:18.520
such as like logistic regression or other types of analyses, depending on things such as standard

00:17:18.520 --> 00:17:27.160
t-tests, ANOVAs, depending on what that is, what's laid out about how analyses occur and in what

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:35.239
order, those kinds of things. So then our work shifted to working with our vendor at the time

00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:41.319
to break down and analyze all of the tables, figures, and listings that we were going to submit.

00:17:42.040 --> 00:17:50.280
So to give everybody an idea of scale, we had about nearly 235 tables, figures, and listings

00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:57.000
that were included in our clinical study report. We had another 120 or so that were not included,

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:05.000
but we still included it as a supplement. You're looking at combing through about 1.8 million data

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:13.319
points on the diary side, 600,000 data points on the study visit side, and then information from

00:18:13.319 --> 00:18:20.280
the device logs and patient uses around 19 million data points as well. So we're working hand-in-hand

00:18:20.280 --> 00:18:25.959
with our vendors to go through that information, make sure that the tables, figures, and listings

00:18:25.959 --> 00:18:29.959
matched on both sides, that we agreed based on the statistical analysis plan that these

00:18:29.959 --> 00:18:36.359
are the numbers we should get. Interesting point here, our vendors used – at this point,

00:18:36.359 --> 00:18:43.880
our vendors used SAS. We did it entirely in R. So we kind of were able to kind of validate it in a way

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:50.520
as we did the analysis there. So as everybody can imagine, you have all those tables,

00:18:50.520 --> 00:18:55.880
figures, and listings. You have one big clinical submission along with the other modules that are

00:18:56.599 --> 00:19:00.280
put together for, like, manufacturing and biocompatibility and all that stuff, and then

00:19:00.280 --> 00:19:05.959
it goes to FDA, and then you enter their review process, which is outlined in the FDA compliance

00:19:05.959 --> 00:19:12.599
program. So typically what that looks like is, you know, going back and forth, they have questions,

00:19:12.599 --> 00:19:19.560
they conduct audits per their compliance program, they have questions about data, you have regular

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:26.040
meetings with them, and then eventually they come to an approval or no approval outcome.

00:19:27.079 --> 00:19:29.160
So we're in the process of doing that.

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:37.479
Thank you. I see Bill had a follow-up question in the chat about using SAS. Bill, do you want

00:19:37.479 --> 00:19:49.400
to jump in? You want me to ask? Okay. It was – well, you answered part of it. Have you used SAS

00:19:49.400 --> 00:19:57.000
in FDA submissions, and did you feel pressure from FDA to use SAS? Can you talk a little bit

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:06.439
about the submission and language user? Yeah. You know, so a lot of this with the

00:20:06.439 --> 00:20:11.239
vendor that we partnered with mainly that was responsible for the submission, they use

00:20:12.199 --> 00:20:20.680
SAS as their standard operating language. So, you know, our expertise was in R at the time and

00:20:20.680 --> 00:20:27.560
continues to be. So we took a very just collaborative hands-on approach with them to

00:20:27.560 --> 00:20:31.479
basically say, okay, every table, figure, and listing that you generate that we agree on,

00:20:31.479 --> 00:20:36.680
we're going to also validate that in R just to make sure that all the numbers align to what we

00:20:36.680 --> 00:20:41.400
want. And also not only align to what we want, but we align based on the understanding of the

00:20:41.400 --> 00:20:46.280
statistical analysis plan, based on the assumptions that are in there, based on the way that things

00:20:46.280 --> 00:20:53.719
were laid up, based on also all the different cuts you were going to give the FDA. So it was

00:20:53.719 --> 00:20:57.959
good. It was actually a positive thing, I think, and Ramil, you can certainly chime in on this,

00:20:58.680 --> 00:21:03.800
that we had a team working together with the vendor and us internally,

00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:09.079
doing analysis kind of also in parallel and being able to come to the same conclusion

00:21:09.880 --> 00:21:15.640
using two different programming languages and having the same understanding of how things should go.

00:21:19.239 --> 00:21:28.199
Rachel, can you hear me? Yes, now I can. Okay. So this is a huge thing. So what I just heard

