00:53:02.280 --> 00:53:11.800
Yeah. So typically for reporting pain, you have a handful of scales that you can do it on. There's

00:53:12.840 --> 00:53:17.080
things like the visual analogue scale where patients will have a scale from zero to 100

00:53:17.080 --> 00:53:21.560
millimetres or so, and they'll actually look at their pain on a millimetre scale and say how high

00:53:22.520 --> 00:53:33.080
it is. We use the NRS zero to 10 scale. And as we worked, our goal with our patients was to really

00:53:33.080 --> 00:53:42.040
kind of understand how they perceive their pain and also worked, you know, with them to help them

00:53:42.040 --> 00:53:48.679
kind of understand how those scales work to help report more accurately. So ultimately though,

00:53:48.679 --> 00:53:57.000
what the patients report is what we received. So in that kind of statement, that's really what it

00:53:57.000 --> 00:54:04.520
is, is you get their pain scores and you try to work with them to help understand their pain,

00:54:04.520 --> 00:54:10.760
you know, because somebody's seven, maybe somebody else is three, for instance. And so it's really

00:54:10.760 --> 00:54:14.919
kind of working with the patient and kind of really understanding and saying, okay, as well,

00:54:15.879 --> 00:54:20.760
I think our field staff did a really great job of this. We heard anecdotally about them

00:54:20.760 --> 00:54:25.320
understanding the patients as well and saying, okay, you're saying your pain might be this level,

00:54:25.320 --> 00:54:31.159
for instance, but look at how much more you're doing today. Is it really there, right? And kind

00:54:31.159 --> 00:54:37.479
of working with the human factor to ensure that we were getting the most accurate reporting as we

00:54:37.479 --> 00:54:43.560
could. But from the data team's point of view, what was reported is what, you know, we took for

00:54:43.560 --> 00:54:50.040
the analysis. So we can't provide medical advice or anything like that. So it is what it is. And

00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:54.919
that's kind of how that worked to ideally get as much high quality data as we could.

